001package squidpony.squidgrid.gui.gdx;

010/**
011 * Allows for the use of custom colors with custom names.
012 * <p>
013 * These colors are comparable for equality but the ordering of them is based on
014 * their hex values.
015 * <p>
016 * Has some built in palettes available as SColor arrays.
017 *
018 * @author Eben Howard - http://squidpony.com - howard@squidpony.com
019 * @see SquidColorCenter Another way to manage colors if you don't want to use preallocated instances.
020 */
021public class SColor extends Color {

8850    /**
8851     * An array of SColor values that should all be fairly different from any other in the group.
8852     * This may be useful for tinting things that should be color-coded differently from each other. To get a random
8853     * order for these colors while still guaranteeing that no color will be drawn twice in the first 56 choices, you
8854     * can use {@code OrderedSet<SColor> palette = new OrderedSet<SColor>(SColor.VARIED_PALETTE).shuffle(rng);} (where
8855     * rng is any non-null RNG) and then get sequential colors from that set with
8856     * {@code int i = 0; SColor color = palette.getAt(i);} , incrementing i before calling getAt again and possibly
8857     * wrapping with {@code i %= 56;} .
8858     * This includes 56 colors, organized in groups of 4 from dark to light in each group:
8859     * <ul>
8860     *     <li>0-3: gray group</li>
8861     *     <li>4-7: brown group</li>
8862     *     <li>8-11: red group</li>
8863     *     <li>12-15: pink group</li>
8864     *     <li>16-19: magenta/purple group</li>
8865     *     <li>20-23: purple/blue-ish group</li>
8866     *     <li>24-27: darker blue group</li>
8867     *     <li>28-31: lighter blue and blue-green group</li>
8868     *     <li>32-35: pure green group</li>
8869     *     <li>36-39: grayish-green group</li>
8870     *     <li>40-43: yellow-green group</li>
8871     *     <li>44-47: yellow group</li>
8872     *     <li>48-51: orange group</li>
8873     *     <li>52-55: orange-red-pink/salmon/coral group</li>
8874     * </ul>
8875     */
8876    public static final SColor[] VARIED_PALETTE = {
8877            DARK_GRAY, GRAY, LIGHT_GRAY, DB_EGGSHELL,
8878            DB_SEAL_BROWN, BROWNER, DARK_TAN, TAN,
8879            DB_BLOOD, PURE_CRIMSON, RED, IBIS_WING,
8880            TREE_PEONY, DEEP_CERISE, HOT_PINK, PINK,
8881            INDIGO, PURPLE, PSYCHEDELIC_PURPLE, LIGHT_VIOLET,
8882            ROYAL_PURPLE, VIOLET, HALF_PURPLE, LAVENDER_FLORAL,
8883            COBALT, CERULEAN_BLUE, BLUE, CORNFLOWER_BLUE,
8884            LIGHT_BLUE_FLOWER, ROBIN_EGG_BLUE, CYAN, LIGHT_BLUE,
8885            GREEN_BAMBOO, PERSIAN_GREEN, ELECTRIC_GREEN, MINT_GREEN,
8886            CAMO_GREEN, PALE_GREEN_ONION, PASTEL_GREEN, MOSS_GREEN,

8916    /**
8917     * A predefined palette of 189 colors derived from 20 hand-picked hues on the color wheel, with 9 variations on
8918     * saturation and value per hue, along with 9 grayscale colors from black to white. Not all of these colors are
8919     * especially distinguishable from each other; this mainly applies to the darkened colors (DARK_, DRAB_, and
8920     * RICH_) and sometimes the saturated colors (FLUSH_, BRIGHT_, and RICH_). The precise meanings of the terms used:
8921     * CW_ is the base color wheel color with medium saturation and value, CW_FADED_ is desaturated, CW_FLUSH_ is
8922     * saturated, CW_LIGHT_ has value increased, CW_PALE_ has value increased and is desaturated, CW_BRIGHT_ has value
8923     * increased and is saturated, CW_DARK_ has value decreased, CW_DRAB_ has value decreased and is desaturated, and
8924     * CW_RICH_ has value decreased and is saturated.
8925     * <br>
8926     * The array is organized into 20 hue blocks of 9 colors each, going from mid-value to light-value to dark-value
8927     * before moving to the next hue block. It starts at red, moves on to orange, yellow, green, blue, purple, and comes
8928     * almost all the way back around to red. It ends with 9 grayscale colors, from black to white, ordered by
8929     * brightness. The grayscale colors use different names, going from darkest to lightest: CW_BLACK, CW_ALMOST_BLACK,
8930     * CW_GRAY_BLACK, CW_DARK_GRAY, CW_GRAY, CW_LIGHT_GRAY, CW_GRAY_WHITE, CW_ALMOST_WHITE, and CW_WHITE.
8931     */
8932    public static final SColor[] COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE = {
8933            CW_RED, CW_FADED_RED, CW_FLUSH_RED, CW_LIGHT_RED, CW_PALE_RED, CW_BRIGHT_RED, CW_DARK_RED, CW_DRAB_RED, CW_RICH_RED,

9267    /**
9268     * Use {@link #intToFloatColor(int)} instead, it's twice as fast on desktop, but still 3x slower than the JDK method
9269     * {@link Float#intBitsToFloat(int)}. {@link com.badlogic.gdx.utils.NumberUtils#intToFloatColor(int)} is now
9270     * super-sourced on GWT with a drastically simpler replacement than the original GWT code, and will use the JDK's
9271     * implementation on desktop where it is much faster, so using NumberUtils should be the way to go.
9272     * @param bits the int to convert to float; only bits in the mask 0xfeffffff will be used
9273     * @return the float that can be used to represent the given bits
9274     */
9275    public static float intToFloatColorAlt(final int bits)
9276    {
9277        return (1f - (bits >>> 30 & 2)) * (0x1.0p0f + 0x0.000002p0f * (bits & 0x7fffff)) *
9278                ((bits & 0x40000000) == 0
9279                        ? (((bits >> 29 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-64f) * ((bits >> 28 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-32f) * ((bits >> 27 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-16f) * ((bits >> 26 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-8f) * ((bits >> 25 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-4f) * 0x1.0p-2f * ((bits >> 23 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-1f))
9280                        : (((bits >> 29 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p64f : 1) * ((bits >> 28 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p32f : 1) * ((bits >> 27 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p16f : 1) * ((bits >> 26 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p8f : 1) * ((bits >> 25 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p4f : 1) * 0x1.0p2f * ((bits >> 23 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-1f))
9281                );
9282    }
9283    /**
9284     * Possible replacement for {@link NumberUtils#intToFloatColor(int)} that is much less complex on GWT; shouldn't be
9285     * called directly and you should default to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.utils.NumberUtils#intToFloatColor(int)}. That
9286     * method is now super-sourced on GWT with a this method as a much simpler replacement for the original GWT code,
9287     * but will not replace the JDK's implementation on desktop where it is much faster. Using NumberUtils should be the
9288     * way to go. For reference, see GWT's source for {@link Float#intBitsToFloat(int)},
9289     * https://gwt.googlesource.com/gwt/+/2.8.0/user/super/com/google/gwt/emul/java/lang/Float.java#96 ,
9290     * which involves multiple if statements, temporary variables, creates a long (slow on GWT), and finally passes off
9291     * control to another method. There's also {@link #rgbToFloatColor(int)} if you don't need to worry about alpha.
9292     *
9293     * @param bits the int to convert to float; only bits in the mask 0xfeffffff will be used
9294     * @return the float that can be used to represent the given bits
9295     */
9296    public static float intToFloatColor(final int bits)
9297    {
9298        return (1 - (bits >>> 30 & 2)) * (1f + 0x0.000002p0f * (bits & 0x7fffff)) *
9299                multipliers[(bits >> 24 & 0x7e) | (bits >> 23 & 1)];
9300    }
9301    public static float rgbToFloatColor(final int rgb)
9302    {
9303        return -(0x1.0p125f + 0x0.000002p125f * (rgb & 0x7fffff)) * ((rgb >> 23 & 1) + 1);
9304    }
9305
9306    /**
9307     * Modifies the color parameter {@code changing} so its value is the one encoded in {@code value}. The way to
9308     * obtain value for libGDX Color objects is with {@link Color#toFloatBits()}, which uses ABGR order, so this
9309     * does some quick work to convert that to RGBA order and assign that into changing.
9310     * @param changing a Color object that will be modified to have the given value
9311     * @param value a value as a float that can be obtained by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}
9312     * @return
9313     */
9314    public static Color colorFromFloat(Color changing, float value)
9315    {
9316        return changing.set(Integer.reverseBytes(NumberUtils.floatToIntColor(value)));
9317    }
9318    static final char[] digits = {
9319            '0', '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6', '7',
9320            '8', '9', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F'};
9321
9322    /**
9323     * Stores the value of color in the char[] {@code changing}, using RGBA8888 format with two hex digits per channel.
9324     * This means that changing must be at least length 8 (this doesn't check for efficiency reasons), and that the
9325     * first two chars represent the red channel from 0 to 255, then the next two are green, then blue. The alpha
9326     * channel is a special case because it represents alpha values between 0 and 254, and effectively rounds down to
9327     * the nearest even number if an odd number value was somehow given to it. For example, opaque white will be shown
9328     * as "FFFFFFFE", and pure red with 50% alpha will be shown as "FF00007E".
9329     * <br>
9330     * The value of {@code color} should be the same type used internally in libGDX and SquidLib, that is, an ABGR
9331     * packed float that could be passed directly to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)}.
9332     *
9333     * @param changing a char array that will be changed in place; must not be null and must have length of at least 8
9334     * @param color a color
9335     * @return
9336     */
9337    public static char[] floatToChars(final char[] changing, final float color)
9338    {
9339        final int i = NumberUtils.floatToIntColor(color);
9340        changing[1] = digits[i & 15];
9341        changing[0] = digits[(i >>> 4) & 15];
9342        changing[3] = digits[(i >>> 8) & 15];
9343        changing[2] = digits[(i >>> 12) & 15];
9344        changing[5] = digits[(i >>> 16) & 15];
9345        changing[4] = digits[(i >>> 20) & 15];
9346        changing[7] = digits[(i >>> 24) & 14]; // mask is 14 due to libGDX avoiding floats that can be NaN
9347        changing[6] = digits[i >>> 28];
9348        return changing;
9349    }
9350
9351    /**
9352     * Meant for usage with {@link #floatToChars(char[], float)}, this will take 8 chars from {@code data} and use them
9353     * to construct an int in RGBA8888 format. Some parts of libGDX use and expect RGBA8888 order, such as most
9354     * constructors for Color and {@link Color#set(int)}, while others use ABGR8888 (often with packed floats), like
9355     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)}, which is the fastest and least wasteful way to set
9356     * the current color used by a Batch for tinting.
9357     * @param data a char array that must not be null and must have length of at least 8
9358     * @param offset where to start reading from in data; there must be at least 8 items between offset and data.length
9359     * @return an int in RGBA8888 format
9360     */
9361    public static int charsToRGBA(final char[] data, final int offset)
9362    {
9363        return StringKit.intFromHex(data, offset, Math.min(data.length, offset+8));
9364    }

9441
9442    /**
9443     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given as 4 RGBA float components. LibGDX expects ABGR format
9444     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
9445     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
9446     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
9447     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
9448     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
9449     * @param r a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for red
9450     * @param g a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for green
9451     * @param b a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for blue
9452     * @param a a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for alpha/opacity
9453     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
9454     */
9455    public static float floatGet(float r, float g, float b, float a)
9456    {
9457        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor(((int)(a * 255) << 24) | ((int)(b * 255) << 16)
9458                | ((int)(g * 255) << 8) | (int)(r * 255));
9459    }
9460
9461    /**
9462     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given an RGBA8888-format long. LibGDX expects ABGR format
9463     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
9464     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
9465     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
9466     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
9467     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
9468     * <br>
9469     * This method is probably not what you want unless you specifically have RGBA8888-format longs that you
9470     * want converted to packed floats. You probably should look at {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)} if
9471     * you have alpha and/or float components, or {@link #floatGetI(int, int, int)} for the common case of the 3 RGB
9472     * components as ints and alpha simply opaque.
9473     * @param c a long with format {@code 32 unused bits, 8 red bits, 8 green bits, 8 blue bits, 7 alpha bits, 1 unused bit}
9474     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
9475     */
9476    public static float floatGet(long c)
9477    {
9478        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor((int)((c >>> 24 & 0xff) | (c >>> 8 & 0xff00) | (c << 8 & 0xff0000)
9479                | (c << 24 & 0xfe000000)));
9480    }

9482    /**
9483     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given an RGBA8888-format int. LibGDX expects ABGR format
9484     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
9485     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
9486     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
9487     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
9488     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
9489     * <br>
9490     * This method is probably not what you want unless you specifically have RGBA8888-format ints that you
9491     * want converted to packed floats. You probably should look at {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)} if
9492     * you have alpha and/or float components, or {@link #floatGetI(int, int, int)} for the common case of the 3 RGB
9493     * components as ints and alpha simply opaque.
9494     * @param c an int with format {@code 8 red bits, 8 green bits, 8 blue bits, 7 alpha bits, 1 unused bit}
9495     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
9496     */
9497    public static float floatGet(int c)
9498    {
9499        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor((c >>> 24) | (c >>> 8 & 0xff00) | (c << 8 & 0xff0000)
9500                | (c << 24));
9501    }

9503    /**
9504     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given as 3 RGB int components, setting alpha to opaque. LibGDX
9505     * expects ABGR format in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR,
9506     * or ARGB. Generally, packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed
9507     * directly to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate
9508     * objects. SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
9509     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
9510     * @param r an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for red
9511     * @param g an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for green
9512     * @param b an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for blue
9513     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
9514     */
9515    public static float floatGetI(int r, int g, int b)
9516    {
9517        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor((r & 0xff) | (g << 8 & 0xff00) | (b << 16 & 0xff0000)
9518                | 0xfe000000); //rgbToFloatColor((b & 0xff) | (g << 8 & 0xff00) | (r << 16));
9519    }
9520
9521    /**
9522     *
9523     * @param hue 0f to 1f, color wheel position
9524     * @param saturation 0f to 1f, 0f is grayscale and 1f is brightly colored
9525     * @param value 0f to 1f, 0f is black and 1f is bright or light
9526     * @param opacity 0f to 1f, 0f is fully transparent and 1f is opaque
9527     * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
9528     */
9529    public static float floatGetHSV(float hue, float saturation, float value, float opacity) {
9530        if ( saturation < 0.004 )                       //HSV from 0 to 1
9531        {
9532            return floatGet(value, value, value, opacity);
9533        }
9534        else
9535        {
9536            final float h = (hue * 6f) % 6f;
9537            final int i = (int)h;             //Or ... var_i = floor( var_h )
9538            final float a = value * ( 1 - saturation );
9539            final float b = value * ( 1 - saturation * ( h - i ) );
9540            final float c = value * ( 1 - saturation * ( 1 - ( h - i ) ) );
9541
9542            switch (i)
9543            {
9544                case 0: return floatGet(value, c, a, opacity);
9545                case 1: return floatGet(b, value, a, opacity);
9546                case 2: return floatGet(a, value, c, opacity);
9547                case 3: return floatGet(a, b, value, opacity);
9548                case 4: return floatGet(c, a, value, opacity);
9549                default: return floatGet(value, a, b, opacity);
9550            }
9551        }
9552    }
9553
9554    @SuppressWarnings("NumericOverflow")
9555    public static float lerpFloatColors(final float start, final float end, final float change)
9556    {
9557        final int s = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(start), e = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(end),
9558                rs = (s & 255), gs = (s & 255 << 8) >>> 8, bs = (s & 255 << 16) >>> 16, as = (s & 254 << 24) >>> 24,
9559                re = (e & 255), ge = (e & 255 << 8) >>> 8, be = (e & 255 << 16) >>> 16, ae = (e & 254 << 24) >>> 24;
9560        return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(((int)(rs + change * (re - rs)) & 0xff)
9561                | ((int)(gs + change * (ge - gs)) & 0xff) << 8
9562                | (((int)(bs + change * (be - bs)) & 0xff) << 16)
9563                | (((int)(as + change * (ae - as)) & 0xfe) << 24));
9564    }
9565
9566    /**
9567     * Similar to {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)}, but meant for an initial state before you have FOV or color
9568     * data to fill the lighting with, and you just need a map of a specific size that starts with no lighting. This
9569     * will produce a map that has white as the lighting color for all cells, but no cells will be lit. It is likely you
9570     * will want to pass this as basis to {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])}.
9571     * @param width the width of the colored lighting area to generate
9572     * @param height the height of the colored lighting area to generate
9573     * @return the colored lighting 3D float array, with no cells lit and all colors set to white
9574     */
9575    public static float[][][] blankColoredLighting(int width, int height)
9576    {
9577        return new float[][][]
9578                {
9579                        new float[width][height],
9580                        ArrayTools.fill(-0x1.fffffep126f, width, height)
9581                };
9582    }
9583
9584    /**
9585     * Removes any information from the given 3D float array for colored lighting, making it as if it had just been
9586     * built by {@link #blankColoredLighting(int, int)}, but without any allocations. This blank state is different from
9587     * being simply filled with all 0 or all default values; the two sub-arrays receive different contents (the one that
9588     * stores brightness is all 0, the one that stores colors will be filled with the float that encodes white).
9589     * @param original a 3d float array used for colored lighting; will be modified to be completely blank
9590     * @return original, after modification
9591     */
9592    public static float[][][] eraseColoredLighting(float[][][] original)
9593    {
9594        ArrayTools.fill(original[0], 0f);
9595        ArrayTools.fill(original[1], -0x1.fffffep126f);
9596        return original;
9597    }
9598    /**
9599     * Given a 2D double array that was probably produced by FOV and a packed color as a float, this gets a 3D float
9600     * array (really just two same-size 2D float arrays in one parent array) that stores the brightnesses in the first
9601     * 2D array element and the colors in the second 2D array element (using the given color if a cell has a value in
9602     * lights that is greater than 0, or defaulting to white if the cell is unlit). This has little use on its own, and
9603     * is meant to be given to {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])} so that multiple colors of lights
9604     * can be mixed.
9605     * @param lights a 2D double array that should probably come from FOV
9606     * @param color a packed float as produced by {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)}
9607     * @return a 3D float array containing two 2D sub-arrays, the first holding brightness and the second holding color
9608     */
9609    public static float[][][] colorLighting(double[][] lights, float color)
9610    {
9611        return colorLightingInto(new float[2][lights.length][lights[0].length], lights, color);
9612    }
9613    /**
9614     * Given a 2D double array that was probably produced by FOV and a packed color as a float, this assigns into reuse
9615     * a 3D float array (really just two same-size 2D float arrays in one parent array) that stores the brightnesses in
9616     * the first 2D array element and the colors in the second 2D array element (using the given color if a cell has a
9617     * value in lights that is greater than 0, or defaulting to white if the cell is unlit). This method requires that
9618     * reuse has length of at least 2, where elements 0 and 1 must be 2D arrays of identical dimensions; this is the
9619     * format that {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)} produces. This has little use on its own, and  is meant to
9620     * be given to {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])} so that multiple colors of lights can be mixed.
9621     * @param reuse
9622     *              a 3D float array of the exact format produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)} or
9623     *              {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])}, and must have length 2; will be modified!
9624     * @param lights a 2D double array that should probably come from FOV
9625     * @param color a packed float as produced by {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)}
9626     * @return reuse after modification
9627     */
9628    public static float[][][] colorLightingInto(float[][][] reuse, double[][] lights, float color)
9629    {
9630        for (int x = 0; x < lights.length; x++) {
9631            for (int y = 0; y < lights[0].length; y++) {
9632                reuse[1][x][y] = ((reuse[0][x][y] = (float) lights[x][y]) > 0f)
9633                        ? color
9634                        : -0x1.fffffep126f; // the color white as a float
9635            }
9636        }
9637        return reuse;
9638    }
9639
9640    /**
9641     * Adds two 3D arrays produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)} or this method and modifies the basis
9642     * parameter so it contains the combined brightnesses and colors of basis and other, in a pair of 2D arrays.
9643     * @param basis a 3D float array holding two 2D sub-arrays, as produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)}; will be modified!
9644     * @param other a 3D float array holding two 2D sub-arrays, as produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)}; will not be modified
9645     * @return basis, after modification; it can be passed to this method as basis again
9646     */
9647    public static float[][][] mixColoredLighting(float[][][] basis, float[][][] other)
9648    {
9649        int w = basis[0].length, h = basis[0][0].length;
9650        for (int x = 0; x < w && x < w; x++) {
9651            for (int y = 0; y < h && y < h; y++) {
9652                basis[1][x][y] = (basis[1][x][y] == -0x1.fffffep126f) // white as float
9653                        ? other[1][x][y]
9654                        : (other[1][x][y] == -0x1.fffffep126f) // white as float
9655                        ? basis[1][x][y]
9656                        : lerpFloatColors(basis[1][x][y], other[1][x][y], (other[0][x][y] - basis[0][x][y]) * 0.5f + 0.5f);
9657                basis[0][x][y] = Math.min(1.0f, basis[0][x][y] + other[0][x][y]);
9658            }
9659        }
9660        return basis;
9661    }

9665    public String toString() {
9666        return name + " " + super.toString();
9667    }

9669    public String getName() {
9670        return name;
9671    }

9673    @Override
9674    public boolean equals(Object other) {
9675        return (other instanceof SColor || other instanceof Color) && toIntBits() == ((Color) other).toIntBits();
9676    }
9677
9678    @Override
9679    public int hashCode() {
9680        return  (155 + CrossHash.Wisp.hash(name)) * 31 + toIntBits();
9681    }
